            Trigonalyidae
(
Hymenoptera
) is a globally distributed small family of rarely collected wasps belonging to the superfamily, Trigonalyiodea, encompassing some 123 species (

; 

; 

). Most species thrive in tropical and subtropical regions, with only one species documented in Europe and a complete absence observed in arctic and alpine habitats (

). Based on morphological phylogenetic analysis there are two recognised subfamilies of 
Trigonalyidae
viz., Orthogonalyinae and 
Trigonalyinae
(

).

The specimens included in the present study were collected by hand and via Malaise trapping from Karnataka and Arunachal Pradesh ( Fig. 6 ). Specimens were treated with hexamethyldisilazane (
) and later dried and pinned. Images were taken with a Keyence VHX-6000 digital microscope and Olympus OM-D with 60 mm lens. The distribution map was made using QGIS 3.30. Morphological terminology is adapted from
. Cuticular sculpture terminology follows Harris (1979).

